          "content": "Greek polis such as Athens and Sparta pioneered democracy, philosophy, and artistic conventions that spread throughout the Mediterranean.  After Alexander’s conquests, the Hellenistic world blended Greek and Eastern cultures, setting the stage for Roman hegemony.  The Roman Republic (509‑27 BCE) and later Empire (27 BCE‑476 CE) forged a pan‑Mediterranean system of roads, law, and administration; the state‑run postal system, the *cursus publicus*, was instituted in 20 BCE (Fact F003; McNeill & Stout 2010, p. 254)."
