          "title": "E. Classical Antiquity: Greek City‑States, Hellenistic World, Roman Republic and Empire",
          "content": "Greek polis such as Athens and Sparta pioneered democracy, philosophy, and artistic conventions that spread throughout the Mediterranean.  After Alexander’s conquests, the Hellenistic world blended Greek and Eastern cultures, setting the stage for Roman hegemony.  The Roman Republic (509‑27 BCE) and later Empire (27 BCE‑476 CE) forged a pan‑Mediterranean system of roads, law, and administration; the state‑run postal system, the *cursus publicus*, was instituted in 20 BCE (Fact F003; McNeill & Stout 2010, p. 254)."
        },
        {
          "title": "F. Late Antiquity and the Transformation of the Roman World",
          "content": "From the third to fifth centuries CE, the Roman world faced internal fragmentation, economic strain, and external pressure from Germanic migrations.  The conversion to Christianity under Constantine and the eventual split of the empire into Western and Eastern halves redefined political and cultural boundaries, culminating in the fall of Rome (476 CE) and the survival of the Eastern Roman (Byzantine) empire."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "II. The Middle Ages (800 – 1453)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. Carolingian Empire and Feudal Foundations",
          "content": "Charlemagne’s coronation on 25 December 800 CE by Pope Leo III (Fact F004; Hall 1995, p. 89) unified much of Western Europe under a revived imperial authority.  The empire’s administrative reforms—such as the *missi dominici*—laid the groundwork for the feudal hierarchy of lords, vassals, and serfs that dominated medieval socio‑political organization."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Viking Age and Early Eastern Expansions",
          "content": "From the late 8th to the 11th centuries, Norse seafarers raided, traded, and settled across the British Isles, the Baltic, and the riverine routes of Eastern Europe, establishing the Kievan Rus’ and influencing the formation of early Russian statehood."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. The Rise of the Papacy and Church‑State Relations",
          "content": "The papacy asserted spiritual supremacy over secular rulers, culminating in the Investiture Controversy (11th‑12th c.) and the formulation of canon law, which framed the balance of power between Rome and emerging monarchies."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Crusades, Trade Leagues and Urbanisation",
          "content": "The Crusades (1096‑1291) mobilised European knights toward the Holy Land, fostering cross‑Cultural exchange and the growth of merchant leagues such as the Hanseatic League, which linked Baltic ports and stimulated urban development."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Intellectual Revival: Scholasticism and Universities",
          "content": "Scholasticism, epitomised by Thomas Aquinas, reconciled Aristotelian philosophy with Christian doctrine.  The rise of universities (e.g., Bologna, Paris, Oxford) institutionalised higher learning and produced a trans‑European intellectual network."
        },
        {
          "title": "F. The Black Death and Socio‑Economic Consequences",
          "content": "The Black Death (1347‑1351) decimated 30‑45 % of Europe’s population (Fact F005; Wells 2014, p. 202), precipitating labor shortages, declining feudal rents, and the eventual shift toward wage labour and market‑oriented agriculture."
        },
        {
          "title": "G. The Hundred Years’ War, Balkan Crises, and the Fall of Constantinople",
          "content": "The protracted Anglo‑French conflict (1337‑1453) reshaped national identities and military technology (e.g., longbow, cannon).  Simultaneously, the Ottoman expansion culminated in the 1453 fall of Constantinople, ending the Byzantine Empire and marking a decisive shift in East‑West geopolitics."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "III. Early Modern Europe (1453 – 1789)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. Renaissance Humanism and Artistic Flourishing",
          "content": "Humanist scholars revived classical texts, influencing art, literature, and politics.  Figures such as Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo embodied the synthesis of scientific inquiry and aesthetic innovation."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Reformation, Counter‑Reformation and Religious Wars",
          "content": "Martin Luther’s posting of the 95 Theses on 31 October 1517 (Fact F007; Merriman 1996, p. 73) ignited the Protestant Reformation.  The ensuing confessional conflict triggered the Thirty Years’ War (1618‑1648), reshaping the religious map of Central Europe."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. Age of Exploration, Colonial Enterprises and Mercantilism",
          "content": "The Treaty of Tordesillas (1494) divided the New World between Spain and Portugal (Fact F008; Kennedy 1987, p. 112).  European powers established overseas empires, instituting mercantilist policies that linked colonial extraction to metropolitan wealth."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Scientific Revolution and Enlightenment Thought",
          "content": "Groundbreaking works by Copernicus, Galileo, Newton, and later Enlightenment philosophers (e.g., Voltaire, Kant) transformed conceptions of nature, society, and governance, laying intellectual foundations for modern democracy."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Absolutism, Constitutionalism and State‑building",
          "content": "Monarchs such as Louis XIV of France instituted centralized bureaucracies, while England’s Glorious Revolution (1688) birthed constitutional monarchy.  Habsburg, Russian, and Ottoman rulers simultaneously pursued territorial consolidation, creating a patchwork of absolute and constitutional states."
        },
        {
          "title": "F. Economic Transformations: Early Capitalism, Textile Industry, and Agricultural Changes",
          "content": "The rise of a market‑oriented economy manifested in the growth of the textile sector, especially in England’s Lancashire, and in agricultural innovations such as the British Enclosure Acts, which shifted production toward commodified farming."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "IV. Revolutionary and Napoleonic Era (1789 – 1815)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. French Revolution: Causes, Phases and Global Impact",
          "content": "Social inequality, fiscal crises, and Enlightenment ideas sparked the 1789 Revolution.  The National Convention abolished the monarchy on 21 September 1792, proclaiming the First French Republic (Fact F009; Clark 2012, p. 183).  The Revolution exported republican ideals across Europe, provoking monarchic coalitions."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Rise of Napoleon Bonaparte and the Napoleonic Wars",
          "content": "Napoleon’s 1799 coup ushered in an authoritarian regime that pursued continental domination.  The Battle of Leipzig (16‑19 Oct 1813), known as the ‘Battle of Nations’, assembled over 600,000 troops and signaled the collapse of French hegemony (Fact F010; Leggett 2000, p. 221)."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. Spread of Nationalist and Liberal Ideals",
          "content": "Napoleonic legal reforms (e.g., the *Code Civil*) codified equality before the law, while his conquests seeded nationalist sentiments that later fueled unification movements in Italy and Germany."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Redrawing of the European Map: Congress of Vienna",
          "content": "The 1815 Congress of Vienna restored a balance of power, reconstructing borders to contain France and establishing a framework for diplomatic congresses that would dominate 19th‑century European politics."
        }
      ]
    },
