        {
          "title": "A. Industrial Revolution: Technological Innovation and Social Change",
          "content": "Britain’s cotton output surged from 1.2 million bales (1780) to 9 million bales (1850), powered by mechanisation and colonial raw material supplies (Fact F011; Burke 2005, p. 156).  Railways, steam engines, and later electricity transformed production and mobility across the continent."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Unification of Italy and Germany",
          "content": "Italian unification culminated in 1861 under Victor Emmanuel II, while the German Empire was proclaimed on 18 January 1871 at Versailles after the Franco‑Prussian War (Fact F012; Kennedy 1987, p. 317).  Both processes reshaped the European balance of power and intensified nationalist competition."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. Imperial Competition and the Scramble for Africa",
          "content": "European powers intensified colonial expansion in Africa (1880‑1914), integrating the continent into global trade networks and intensifying rivalries that would later feed into World War I."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Social Movements: Labour, Women’s Suffrage, and Early Socialism",
          "content": "Industrialisation spurred labour organisations (e.g., the 1848 International Workingmen’s Association) and catalysed women’s suffrage campaigns, while Marxist and socialist ideas gained traction across Europe."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Cultural Modernism: Literature, Music, Visual Arts",
          "content": "The fin de siècle saw artistic experimentation—Impressionist painting, Symbolist poetry, and the music of Wagner—reflecting the anxieties and dynamism of a rapidly changing continent."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "VI. The World at War (1914 – 1945)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. World War I: Causes, Conduct, and Consequences",
          "content": "The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand on 28 June 1914 sparked a web of alliances that expanded into a full‑scale war by August 1914 (Fact F013; Clark 2012, p. 45).  Trench warfare, total mobilisation, and the 1917 Russian Revolution reshaped the political map of Europe."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Interwar Europe: Treaty of Versailles, League of Nations, Economic Crises",
          "content": "The 1919 Treaty imposed punitive reparations on Germany, sowing resentment.  The League of Nations proved ineffective, while the Great Depression of the 1930s destabilised democracies and exacerbated extremist politics."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. Rise of Totalitarian Regimes: Fascism, Nazism, Stalinism",
          "content": "Economic hardship and nationalist rhetoric facilitated the rise of Mussolini’s fascist Italy, Hitler’s Nazi Germany, and Stalin’s totalitarian Soviet Union, each employing mass mobilisation and ideological control (see Debate Summary on totalitarianism)."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. World War II: European Front, Holocaust, Resistance Movements",
          "content": "Operation Overlord began on 6 June 1944, with 156,000 Allied troops landing on Normandy beaches (Fact F014; Kershaw 2000, p. 312).  The Holocaust resulted in the murder of six million Jews, and resistance networks across occupied Europe undermined Nazi control."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Post‑war Reconstruction: Marshall Plan, United Nations, NATO",
          "content": "The Marshall Plan delivered approximately US $13 billion (≈ US $140 billion in 2020 dollars) to Western Europe between 1948‑1952 (Fact F015; Post‑war 2005, p. 67), catalysing economic recovery and political stabilisation, while NATO provided a collective security framework."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "VII. Cold War Europe (1945 – 1991)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. Division of Europe: Iron Curtain and Bipolar Order",
          "content": "Post‑1945 Europe split into NATO‑aligned Western bloc and Soviet‑dominated Eastern bloc, with the ‘Iron Curtain’ symbolising the physical and ideological division."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. European Integration: European Coal & Steel Community → European Union",
          "content": "The 1951 European Coal & Steel Community laid the foundation for supranational governance, eventually culminating in the 1992 Maastricht Treaty, which formally created the European Union and introduced the three‑pillar structure (Fact F016; Jones 2004, p. 23)."
        },
        {
          "title": "C. Decolonisation and Post‑colonial Migration",
          "content": "European de‑imperialisation after WWII produced massive migration from former colonies, transforming demographic patterns and prompting debates over multiculturalism and integration."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Cultural Revolutions: 1968, Counter‑culture, New Left",
          "content": "Student protests, anti‑war movements, and the rise of New Left politics challenged traditional authority structures and reshaped cultural norms across the continent."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Economic Transformations: Welfare State, Post‑war Boom, Oil Crises",
          "content": "Western European welfare states expanded, providing universal health care, education, and social security.  The 1973 oil crisis, however, exposed vulnerabilities, prompting new economic policies."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "VIII. Contemporary Europe (1991 – 2025)",
      "subsections": [
        {
          "title": "A. Post‑Cold‑War Expansion and EU Enlargement",
          "content": "The 2004 EU enlargement added ten Central and Eastern European states, increasing membership from 15 to 25 (Fact F017; Garton‑Ash 1999, p. 140).  Subsequent enlargements integrated the Balkans and the Baltic states."
        },
        {
          "title": "B. Eurozone and Monetary Integration",
          "content": "The introduction of the euro in 1999 created a single currency for most EU members, fostering deeper economic convergence while also exposing asymmetries revealed during the 2008 financial crisis."
        },
