          "title": "C. Challenges to Liberal Democracy: Populism, Migration Crises, Brexit",
          "content": "The United Kingdom’s 2016 referendum voted to leave the EU with 51.9 % support for ‘Leave’ (Fact F018; Monaco 2023, p. 11).  Simultaneously, right‑wing populist movements gaining ground across Europe sparked debates on cultural backlash versus economic insecurity (see Debate Summary)."
        },
        {
          "title": "D. Technological Change, Digital Economy and Green Transition",
          "content": "By 2023, 94 % of EU households had internet access, and the Digital Services Act (2022) became the first comprehensive regulation of online platforms (Fact F020; Taylor 2022, p. 78).  The European Green Deal aims to achieve climate neutrality by 2050."
        },
        {
          "title": "E. Security and Geopolitics: Russia‑Ukraine Conflict, NATO‑EU Relations, China’s Influence",
          "content": "Russia’s full‑scale invasion of Ukraine began on 24 February 2022, prompting unprecedented EU sanctions (Fact F019; Rossi 2022, p. 5).  This conflict renewed NATO‑EU security cooperation while raising concerns about China’s growing economic and diplomatic footprint."
        },
        {
          "title": "F. Cultural Diversity, Identity Debates and the Future of European Unity",
          "content": "Contemporary discourse reflects tensions between supranational identity and regional/national particularism, with scholarship highlighting both the ‘cultural backlash’ and the ‘economic precarity’ dimensions of populist surges (Norris 2019; Mudde 2019)."
        }
